{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d32142b8-a4cf-4deb-b0e9-5b65baee38a5","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (default `http://localhost:6274`) that proxies to your server over stdio.\n\n**In the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse **Tools**, **Resources**, and **Prompts** your server exposes\n- Execute tools with custom JSON inputs and see responses\n- View the raw JSON-RPC message exchange for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- If your server needs arguments, append them: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./Server.csproj -- --my-flag`\n- Set a custom port with `--port 8080` if 6274 is taken\n- Use `--method stdio` explicitly if auto-detection fails\n- Check the **Messages** tab to inspect the `initialize` handshake and verify capabilities\n\nThis gives you a fast feedback loop without needing a full LLM client.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a622352e-6c12-437b-9ef2-7d4823a15632","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise, helpful answer about using the MCP Inspector with a stdio-based C# server.","outputTokens":347,"requestId":"CC28:1D180A:7ED7221:8D27F55:69EAC14A"},"id":"910cbd91-1473-42cb-afef-a06d35892e8d","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:03:15.253Z","parentId":"513fa277-9c51-46f2-a03c-dabf5ce64e87"}
